In this article, President Joseph R. Biden Jr. discusses the importance of National Sexual Assault Awareness and Prevention Month. He acknowledges that sexual violence is a widespread issue that affects people of all backgrounds and emphasizes the need to change the culture that allows it to persist. President Biden highlights the significance of consent and the criminal nature of sexual assault. He also mentions his involvement in the Violence Against Women Act (VAWA) and its impact on preventing and prosecuting sexual assault, providing support for survivors, and expanding protections for marginalized communities. The article further outlines various initiatives and reforms aimed at helping survivors, reducing backlogs of untested rape kits, improving trauma-informed training for law enforcement, and ensuring justice for victims. President Biden also addresses the issue of sexual assault in the military and workplace, as well as the importance of campus prevention efforts and the protection of students from discrimination. He urges all Americans to support survivors and join the fight against sexual assault. The article concludes with President Biden proclaiming April 2023 as National Sexual Assault Awareness and Prevention Month.